<h1>Adjectives</h1>

<p>
Japanese adjectives are split into two classes: @HI{{i}}-adjectives and @HI{{na}}-adjectives. They can be used prenominally, like adjectives
in English, to modify a noun, but they can also be used as a predicate.
</p>

<p>
When used as a predicate, @HI{{i}}-adjectives can occur at the end of a sentence in the plain form. If the sentence is to be in
the polite form then the @HI{{i}}-adjective will be followed by desu. As shown in the table, the @HI{{i}}-adjective inflects to
show whether the sentence is in the past and whether the sentence is in the negative. In all these cases the difference between
the plain form and the polite form is the presence of a final @HI{{desu}}. Note that this @HI{{desu}} does not inflect as
a <a href="grammar-copula.html">copula</a>, but remains unchanged and merely marks the sentence as being in the polite form.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{wealth^gentleman^mountain}}ha@KJ{{tall}}idesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mt. Fuji is tall.
  </td> </tr>
</table>

<p>
When used prenominally, @HI{{i}}-adjectives precede the modified noun with no intervening part of speech required..

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{wealth^gentleman^mountain}}ha@KJ{{tall}}i@KJ{{mountain}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mt. Fuji is a high mountain.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
When used as a predicate, @HI{{na}}-adjectives are found, without the @HI{{na}}, followed by the 
<a href="grammar-copula.html">copula<a/>. It is the copula
that inflects to show a sentence that is in the past or in the negative. The form of the shows whether
the sentence is in the plain form of the polite form.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{watto}}@KJ{{before^life}}ha@KJ{{parent^cut}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Watt is kind.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
When used prenominally, a @HI{{na}} is placed between the @HI{{na}}-adjectives and the modified noun.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{watto}}@KJ{{before^life}}ha@KJ{{parent^cut}}na@KJ{{before^life}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Watt is a kind teacher.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
Adjective sentences form questions in the same way as noun or verb sentences: by taking a sentence-ending
<a href="grammar-particle-ka.html">@HI{{ka}}</a>. The answre should repeat the adjective.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{pekinn}}ha@KJ{{cold}}idesuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{hai,@KJ{{cold}}idesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Is it cold in Beijing?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Yes it is.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>
</p>

<h1>@HI{{i}}-adjectives</h1>

<table class="example">
 <tr>
   <th> &nbsp; </th>
   <th> Informal </th>
   <th> Formal </th>
 </tr>
 <tr>
   <td> Present </td>
   <td> @HI{{taka}}<span>@HI{{i}}</span></td>
   <td> @HI{{taka}}<span>@HI{{i desu}}</span></td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
   <td> Present Negative </td>
   <td> @HI{{taka}}<span>@HI{{kunai}}</span></td>
   <td> @HI{{taka}}<span>@HI{{kunai desu}}</span></td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
   <td> Past</td>
   <td> @HI{{taka}}<span>@HI{{katta}}</span></td>
   <td> @HI{{taka}}<span>@HI{{katta desu}}</span></td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
   <td> Past Negative</td>
   <td> @HI{{taka}}<span>@HI{{kunakatta}}</span></td>
   <td> @HI{{taka}}<span>@HI{{kunakatta desu}}<span></td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
   <td> @HI{{te}}-form</td>
   <td> @HI{{taka}}<span>@HI{{kute}}</span></td>
   <td> @HI{{taka}}<span>@HI{{kute}}<span></td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
   <td> Adverb</td>
   <td> @HI{{taka}}<span>@HI{{ku}}</span></td>
   <td> @HI{{taka}}<span>@HI{{ku}}<span></td>
 </tr>
</table>

<h1>@HI{{na}}-adjectives</h1>

<table class="example">
 <tr>
   <th> &nbsp; </th>
   <th> Informal </th>
   <th> Formal </th>
 </tr>
 <tr>
   <td> Present </td>
   <td> @HI{{benri}}<span>@HI{{ da}}</span></td>
   <td> @HI{{benri}}<span>@HI{{ desu}}</span></td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
   <td> Present Negative </td>
   <td> @HI{{benri}}<span>@HI{{ dewa nai}}</span></td>
   <td> @HI{{benri}}<span>@HI{{ dewa arimasenn}}</span></td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
   <td> Past</td>
   <td> @HI{{benri}}<span>@HI{{ datta}}</span></td>
   <td> @HI{{benri}}<span>@HI{{ deshita}}</span></td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
   <td> Past Negative</td>
   <td> @HI{{benri}}<span>@HI{{dewa nakatta}}</span></td>
   <td> @HI{{benri}}<span>@HI{{dewa arimasenn deshita}}<span></td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
   <td> @HI{{te}}-form</td>
   <td> @HI{{benri}}<span>@HI{{de}}</span></td>
   <td> @HI{{benri}}<span>@HI{{de}}<span></td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
   <td> Adverb</td>
   <td> @HI{{benri}}<span>@HI{{ni}}</span></td>
   <td> @HI{{benri}}<span>@HI{{ni}}<span></td>
 </tr>
</table>

<h1>Comparatives</h1>

<p>
In a comparison the other item is marked with @HI{{yori}} and the adjective is left unchanged.
</p>

